"""
mkt-christ fill — 1 Kings ch1-2
Covers: 95 missing verses (ch1: 1-38, 40-47, 49-53; ch2: 1-9, 11-28, 29-34, 36-46)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1kings-1-2-fill.py

Key typological decisions:
- Solomon = primary messianic type: son of David, king of peace, builder of the temple
- Adonijah = anti-type: self-exaltation vs. Christ's appointment by the Father (Ps 2:6)
- Gihon anointing (1:39) = OT type of Spirit-anointing; fulfilled in Christ's baptism
- David's final charge (2:1-4) = covenant stipulation; Christ fulfills all the law perfectly
- Davidic throne promise (2:4, 2:45) = 2 Sam 7 covenant; Christ its eternal fulfillment
- Abiathar's removal (2:27) = prophetic fulfillment pattern; Scripture moves toward Christ
"""

import json
import pathlib

def load_comm(path):
    p = pathlib.Path(path)
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(path, data):
    pathlib.Path(path).write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new commentary entries without overwriting existing ones — safe to re-run
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
"1": {
"1": "<p>The chapter opens with David aged and cold — every human king is provisional. Even Israel&#8217;s greatest Davidic ruler fails with time, his body unable to generate warmth. Christologically, this frailty sets the stage for the true Son of David who possesses life in himself (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 5:26'>John 5:26</a>): the eternal warmth David lacks, Christ embodies. Every human succession narrative ultimately asks for a king who does not grow old.</p>",
"2": "<p>The court&#8217;s proposal to seek a young woman to attend and warm the king is a purely human remedy for human frailty. The root <em>yᵉḵahēn</em> (minister before him) shares its form with priestly service. Human ingenuity can provide a caretaker but cannot restore a king&#8217;s life; only the resurrection of the Son of David transcends the decline all flesh undergoes.</p>",
"3": "<p>Abishag the Shunammite is found — beautiful, caring for the king in his weakness. She comes from Shunem, the town of Elisha&#8217;s benefactress (2 Kgs 4), linking the two great prophetic cycles. Those who minister to kings in their weakness foreshadow those who attend Christ in his: the women at the crucifixion who remain when the disciples flee, and those who first proclaim the resurrection.</p>",
"4": "<p>The explicit note that David did not &#8220;know&#8221; Abishag (<em>wᵉhammelek lōʾ yᵉḏāʿāh</em>) prevents her from being legally a wife or concubine, which becomes important in ch2 when Adonijah requests her. David&#8217;s complete physical frailty at life&#8217;s end contrasts with the risen Christ&#8217;s eternal vitality — the true Son of David reigns in imperishable life, not declining flesh.</p>",
"5": "<p>Adonijah&#8217;s self-declaration — <em>ʾănî ʾemloḵ</em> (I will be king) — is the anti-type of messianic appointment. No legitimate king appoints himself; the true king receives kingship from the Father&#8217;s decree (<a class='ref' data-ref='Ps 2:6'>Ps 2:6</a>: &#8220;I have set my King on Zion&#8221;; <a class='ref' data-ref='Acts 2:36'>Acts 2:36</a>: &#8220;God has made him both Lord and Christ&#8221;). Adonijah&#8217;s chariots and horsemen contrast with Christ&#8217;s entry on a donkey — the pattern of false and true kingship.</p>",
"6": "<p>David never corrected Adonijah (<em>lōʾ ʿaṣṣāḇô ʾāḇîw</em>). Undisciplined fathers produce sons who claim what is not theirs. Unlike human fathers, the heavenly Father disciplines his Son through suffering to perfection (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 5:8-9'>Heb 5:8–9</a>). Christ&#8217;s perfect submission to the Father is the theological opposite of Adonijah&#8217;s self-promotion — the contrast that defines legitimate and illegitimate kingship.</p>",
"7": "<p>Adonijah&#8217;s coalition unites Joab (military power) and Abiathar (priestly authority) behind the pretender. The alignment of earthly power and institutional religion against the legitimate heir repeats at the passion: the chief priests and Roman governor align against Christ, the true Davidic heir. Human power structures consistently misread divine appointment and align with the wrong claimant.</p>",
"8": "<p>The counter-coalition for Solomon gathers prophet (Nathan), priest (Zadok), and warrior (Benaiah) — the three offices that together authenticate legitimate kingship. Christ alone holds prophet, priest, and king in one person, the personal union of what these three represent. Solomon&#8217;s legitimacy requires three separate men; the Messiah embodies all three offices inseparably.</p>",
"9": "<p>Adonijah&#8217;s feast at the Serpent&#8217;s Stone before his kingship is confirmed is an unauthorized banquet — a pattern of premature possession. Like Adam&#8217;s unauthorized eating before the time of God&#8217;s gift, the usurper&#8217;s feast must be interrupted by the legitimate anointing. The messianic banquet (Isa 25:6) is the legitimate feast; all others are premature pretensions.</p>",
"10": "<p>The deliberate exclusions from Adonijah&#8217;s feast — Nathan, Benaiah, the mighty men, Solomon — mark precisely those who carry the prophetic-covenantal succession. To be excluded from the pretender&#8217;s banquet is protection, not loss. Those outside the usurper&#8217;s circle are free to receive the legitimate king. The Gospels record similar exclusions: the establishment excludes tax collectors and sinners, who then become the guests of the true feast.</p>",
"11": "<p>Nathan approaches Bathsheba with prophetic urgency: have you not heard that Adonijah has become king? The prophet perceives the usurpation before others do and mobilizes intervention. This parallels Nathan&#8217;s confrontation of David in 2 Sam 12 — both times the prophet guards the Davidic covenant. Prophetic office exists to protect the covenant line through which the Messiah comes.</p>",
"12": "<p>Nathan&#8217;s counsel aims to protect both Bathsheba&#8217;s life and Solomon&#8217;s — to protect Solomon is to protect the covenantal heir. Nathan functions as advocate for the legitimate king, a role the Spirit fulfills for the sons of the true Davidic King (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 8:27'>Rom 8:27</a>). Political advocacy and theological faithfulness are united in Nathan&#8217;s intervention.</p>",
"13": "<p>Nathan instructs Bathsheba to remind David of his oath: &#8220;Did you not swear that Solomon your son shall reign after me?&#8221; The oath of a king is the ground of the covenant; when divine promises are in danger of being usurped, those within the covenant appeal to the sworn word. Christ&#8217;s intercession is similarly an appeal to the Father&#8217;s sworn oath: &#8220;Once for all I have sworn by my holiness&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Ps 89:35'>Ps 89:35</a>).</p>",
"14": "<p>Nathan promises to follow Bathsheba into the king&#8217;s presence and confirm her words — a double witness establishing the claim according to legal testimony (Deut 17:6; 19:15). The two-witness pattern runs through Scripture as the standard of verified truth; ultimately fulfilled in Christ who is himself the Truth, and whose resurrection was attested by many witnesses (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 15:6'>1 Cor 15:6</a>).</p>",
"15": "<p>Bathsheba enters the king&#8217;s room where Abishag the Shunammite is attending him. The scene of intercession before an aged king foreshadows the queen-mother theology in Davidic succession: Bathsheba as queen mother interceding for her son&#8217;s rights before the king. The intercessory role of the queen mother in Judah (cf. Jer 13:18) provides a human analogy for intercession before the throne.</p>",
"16": "<p>Bathsheba bows in homage (<em>wayyiqqōḏ lammamelek</em>) before asking her petition. Proper approach to the king requires submission before petition — the posture of the one who intercedes. The same pattern governs access to the divine throne: approach with reverence before request. Bathsheba&#8217;s homage frames her petition as an act of loyalty rather than demand.</p>",
"17": "<p>Bathsheba recalls the oath: &#8220;you swore to me by the LORD your God — Solomon your son shall reign after me.&#8221; The oath by YHWH makes this a theologically binding covenant, not merely a political promise. The reliability of the Davidic covenant ultimately rests not on human memory or political succession but on YHWH&#8217;s own sworn word, which Christ fulfills as the eternal Son of David.</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;Yet now Adonijah has become king, and you, my lord the king, do not know it&#8221; — the usurpation has proceeded to near-completion while the legitimate appointer was unaware. The crisis of uninformed kingship mirrors the parable of the nobleman who went to receive a kingdom while his citizens rejected him (Luke 19:12–14). The legitimate king&#8217;s apparent absence is precisely when usurpers act.</p>",
"19": "<p>Adonijah has feasted with the king&#8217;s sons, the army commander, and Abiathar — all the king&#8217;s sons except Solomon, the explicitly covenantal heir. The pattern of including all but the chosen one recurs in Scripture: Saul is anointed when all human candidates are exhausted; David is called in from the field when Jesse presents all his sons. The chosen heir is consistently the unexpected one.</p>",
"20": "<p>&#8220;All Israel is looking to you to announce who will sit on the throne after you&#8221; — the people&#8217;s gaze is on the king for the succession declaration. Messianic expectation is the posture of Israel throughout its history: waiting for the declaration of who will sit on David&#8217;s throne. The NT presents the Father&#8217;s declaration at the baptism and transfiguration: &#8220;This is my beloved Son&#8221; — the public designation of the heir.</p>",
"21": "<p>Bathsheba&#8217;s self-description as potential &#8220;offenders&#8221; (<em>ḥaṭṭāʾîm</em>) if Adonijah takes the throne reflects the political reality that rivals to a new king are typically eliminated. The messianic heir&#8217;s legitimacy is ultimately a matter of life and death for those associated with him. To be on the side of the true Davidic heir is the only secure position — a pattern realized in discipleship to Christ.</p>",
"22": "<p>Nathan&#8217;s arrival as Bathsheba finishes speaking provides the double-witness confirmation. Divine timing in the succession narrative — the prophet arriving at precisely the right moment — reflects the providential protection of the covenant line. The Messiah&#8217;s coming is not accidental but the culmination of centuries of such divine timing in Davidic history.</p>",
"23": "<p>Nathan bows with his face to the earth before David — the full prostration reserved for the highest reverence. Even the prophet who had confronted David with &#8220;You are the man&#8221; (2 Sam 12:7) approaches the dying king with complete submission. The prophetic office serves the Davidic covenant; it confronts kings only in faithfulness to the covenant, and submits to legitimate kings as the Lord&#8217;s anointed.</p>",
"24": "<p>Nathan&#8217;s diplomatic question — &#8220;Have you declared that Adonijah shall reign after you?&#8221; — gives David face-saving room rather than direct accusation. The prophet&#8217;s wisdom in advocacy mirrors Christ&#8217;s method of asking questions that lead the interlocutor to self-disclosure (Mark 12:35–37: how can the scribes say the Christ is David&#8217;s son?). Prophetic truth-telling uses questions as much as declarations.</p>",
"25": "<p>Nathan&#8217;s report of Adonijah&#8217;s feast — &#8220;and they are eating and drinking with him and saying, Long live King Adonijah&#8221; — presents the acclamation of the pretender as a fait accompli. The false acclamation of an illegitimate king is a recurring temptation in Israel&#8217;s history. The true acclamation — &#8220;Blessed is the King who comes in the name of the LORD&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 19:38'>Luke 19:38</a>) — is still future in every moment of premature royal announcement.</p>",
"26": "<p>Nathan notes his own exclusion from Adonijah&#8217;s feast — along with Zadok, Benaiah, and Solomon himself. The prophet&#8217;s marginalization from the pretender&#8217;s gathering reinforces that those who carry divine appointment are precisely those the usurper cannot afford to include. The excluded prophet, priest, and legitimate heir together constitute the true royal court awaiting its moment.</p>",
"27": "<p>Nathan&#8217;s closing question: &#8220;Is this done with my lord the king&#8217;s knowledge?&#8221; presses David to declare his will. The prophet&#8217;s question to the king is simultaneously a call to covenant faithfulness — David must either confirm the promise to Solomon or disown it. The question every person must ultimately answer: do you acknowledge the legitimate heir? The NT version: &#8220;Who do you say that I am?&#8221;</p>",
"28": "<p>David summons Bathsheba to stand before him. The king&#8217;s command in response to the double witness initiates the decisive royal action. David&#8217;s gathering of resolve at life&#8217;s end to confirm the covenantal heir mirrors the pattern of dying patriarchs who confirm the covenant succession: Jacob blessing Judah, Moses blessing Joshua. The passing of covenant promises through dying human agents is the method of redemptive history.</p>",
"29": "<p>David&#8217;s oath: &#8220;As YHWH lives, who has redeemed my life from every trouble.&#8221; The invocation of YHWH the redeemer (<em>haGōʾēl ʾet napšî</em>) links the covenant oath to the redemptive theology of the Psalms. David swears not by his own authority but by YHWH who has preserved him. The messianic oath — &#8220;YHWH has sworn and will not change his mind&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Ps 110:4'>Ps 110:4</a>) — similarly grounds the king&#8217;s eternal priesthood in divine fidelity.</p>",
"30": "<p>The reaffirmation of the promise: &#8220;Solomon your son shall reign after me, and he shall sit on my throne in my place.&#8221; The throne is David&#8217;s before it is Solomon&#8217;s; legitimacy flows through succession rather than seizure. The Son of David who fulfills this promise sits on the throne not by coup but by the Father&#8217;s declaration: &#8220;Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies your footstool&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Ps 110:1'>Ps 110:1</a>).</p>",
"31": "<p>Bathsheba bows again and declares: &#8220;May my lord King David live forever!&#8221; (<em>yᵉḥî ʾăḏōnî hammelek dāwîḏ lᵉʿōlām</em>). The blessing she pronounces over David will be fulfilled not in David&#8217;s mortality but in the immortal reign of his greater son. Christ alone, as the true Son of David, lives and reigns forever — the acclamation &#8220;live forever&#8221; finds its permanent referent in him who has &#8220;the keys of death and Hades&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 1:18'>Rev 1:18</a>).</p>",
"32": "<p>David summons Zadok the priest, Nathan the prophet, and Benaiah — the three who form the legitimate succession coalition. The simultaneous summoning of the priestly, prophetic, and military leaders for the anointing ceremony anticipates the messianic office where all three are inseparably united in one person. Solomon&#8217;s anointing requires three men; Christ&#8217;s anointing requires only the Father&#8217;s Spirit descending on the one who is himself prophet, priest, and king.</p>",
"33": "<p>The command: &#8220;Have Solomon ride on my own mule (<em>ʿal happirdāh ʾăšer lî</em>).&#8221; The king&#8217;s personal mount transfers royal authority. The mule was the royal conveyance in Israel (cf. 2 Sam 13:29; 18:9). When Christ enters Jerusalem on a donkey, he is fulfilling precisely this pattern of the king&#8217;s designated mount signaling succession and authority — not merely fulfilling Zech 9:9 as an isolated prophecy but embodying the whole Davidic royal tradition.</p>",
"34": "<p>The anointing command: &#8220;Let Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet anoint him (<em>wᵉmāšᵉḥû ʾōtô šām</em>) king over Israel, and blow the ram&#8217;s horn and say, Long live King Solomon.&#8221; The three elements — anointing with oil, trumpet blast, and public acclamation — constitute the full inauguration ceremony. Christ&#8217;s anointing at his baptism has the same three elements: Spirit-anointing, the Father&#8217;s voice, and the subsequent acclamation of those who recognize him.</p>",
"35": "<p>&#8220;He shall come and sit on my throne, for he is the one I have appointed to be ruler over Israel and over Judah.&#8221; The explicit Davidic appointment — &#8220;the one I have appointed&#8221; (<em>ʾōtô ṣiwwîtî</em>) — grounds Solomon&#8217;s kingship in royal decree rather than popular vote or military strength. Christ&#8217;s appointment as King is similarly grounded in the Father&#8217;s decree: &#8220;I have set my King on Zion&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Ps 2:6'>Ps 2:6</a>). The throne is received, not seized.</p>",
"36": "<p>Benaiah&#8217;s response: &#8220;Amen! May the LORD, the God of my lord the king, say so too.&#8221; The military leader&#8217;s <em>ʾāmēn</em> is a liturgical word of covenant ratification — he is not merely expressing personal approval but aligning himself with the divine decree. The use of <em>ʾāmēn</em> here anticipates its weight in Jesus&#8217; speech: &#8220;Truly, truly I say to you&#8221; (<em>ʾāmēn ʾāmēn</em>) — the one who himself is the &#8220;Amen&#8221; to all God&#8217;s promises (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 1:20'>2 Cor 1:20</a>).</p>",
"37": "<p>Benaiah prays that YHWH will be with Solomon as he was with David, and make Solomon&#8217;s throne greater than David&#8217;s. The prayer for surpassing greatness in the Davidic line is fulfilled in Christ: his throne is not merely greater than David&#8217;s in earthly terms but is an eternal throne at the Father&#8217;s right hand (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 1:8'>Heb 1:8</a>: &#8220;Your throne, O God, is forever and ever&#8221;).</p>",
"38": "<p>The anointing party descends to Gihon: Zadok, Nathan, Benaiah, the Cherethites, and the Pelethites — the full royal guard. The descent to the spring Gihon (Jerusalem&#8217;s primary water source, sacred for royal anointing) establishes the geographic-theological axis of Davidic succession. Gihon&#8217;s water recalls the rivers of Eden (Gen 2:13 — one of the four rivers); the anointing at the water source connects royal inauguration to creation and life.</p>",
"40": "<p>All the people go up after Solomon playing flutes, rejoicing with great joy so that the earth shook. The popular acclamation of the legitimate king — spontaneous, unorchestrated, physically overwhelming — is the crowd&#8217;s response to recognized divine appointment. The same dynamic appears at Jesus&#8217; entry into Jerusalem: the crowd spreads cloaks and branches, crying &#8220;Hosanna&#8221; — an irresistible joy attending the true Davidic heir&#8217;s approach to his throne.</p>",
"41": "<p>Adonijah and his guests hear the tumult while finishing their feast. The sound of the trumpet and the city&#8217;s noise interrupts the pretender&#8217;s celebration. Every false kingdom is ultimately interrupted by the proclamation of the true King. The question &#8220;What is this noise of the city in an uproar?&#8221; (<em>meh qōl hāʿîr hōmeh</em>) echoes the question of Jerusalem when Jesus entered: &#8220;Who is this?&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 21:10'>Matt 21:10</a>).</p>",
"42": "<p>Jonathan son of Abiathar arrives at Adonijah&#8217;s feast as a messenger. Adonijah says &#8220;Come in, for you are a worthy man (<em>ʾîš ḥayil ʾāttāh</em>) and bring good news.&#8221; Ironically, the news Jonathan brings will dissolve the feast. The messenger&#8217;s arrival with unexpected news that overturns the pretender&#8217;s celebration is a recurring pattern: the angel at the tomb dissolves the disciples&#8217; despair; the herald of the king&#8217;s arrival overturns every settled assumption about who is in charge.</p>",
"43": "<p>Jonathan&#8217;s opening — &#8220;not at all, our lord King David has made Solomon king&#8221; — is the gospel within the historical narrative: the legitimate appointment has been made, the pretender&#8217;s claim is over. The announcement of the true king&#8217;s installation is always unwelcome to those who have organized their lives around the pretender. Jonathan&#8217;s &#8220;not at all&#8221; (<em>ʾăḇal</em>) echoes through history wherever the true King&#8217;s appointment is announced.</p>",
"44": "<p>Jonathan lists the anointing party — Zadok, Nathan, Benaiah, the royal guard. The enumeration of the legitimate coalition who carried out the anointing is also a list of those whose loyalty was correctly placed. The roll call of faithful witnesses to the Messiah&#8217;s appointment runs through Scripture: the prophets, the Baptist, the apostles, the Spirit himself — all testify to the one the Father has appointed.</p>",
"45": "<p>&#8220;Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet have anointed him king at Gihon. They have gone up from there rejoicing (<em>śᵉmēḥîm</em>).&#8221; The joy of the anointing party ascending from Gihon is the joy of those who have participated in the installation of the legitimate heir. The joy that follows Christ&#8217;s resurrection and ascension — the disciples returning to Jerusalem &#8220;with great joy&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 24:52'>Luke 24:52</a>) — is this same ascending gladness after the true anointing is confirmed.</p>",
"46": "<p>&#8220;Solomon is now sitting on the royal throne.&#8221; The simple present perfect — the deed is done — marks the transition of power. The legitimate heir is seated. The NT equivalent is Heb 1:3: &#8220;he sat down at the right hand of the Majesty on high&#8221; — the session of the true Son of David on the eternal throne, the simple fact that changes all of history.</p>",
"47": "<p>The king&#8217;s servants come to congratulate David, praying that God make Solomon&#8217;s name more famous than David&#8217;s. The blessing over the successor king from the incumbent&#8217;s servants shows institutional transfer: those who served David now redirect their loyalty to the appointed heir. This models the pattern of faithful Israel&#8217;s transition from Mosaic covenant to new covenant — from the old administration to the new, greater king.</p>",
"49": "<p>Adonijah&#8217;s guests were terrified and dispersed (<em>wayyāqumû wayyēlᵉḵû ʾîš lᵉḏarkô</em>). The pretender&#8217;s coalition collapses the moment the legitimate appointment is confirmed. This pattern recurs at the resurrection: the guards at the tomb shake and become like dead men when the true King&#8217;s vindication is announced. False coalitions built around earthly power cannot withstand the confirmation of divine appointment.</p>",
"50": "<p>Adonijah, afraid of Solomon, seizes the horns of the altar — the classic sanctuary-refuge position. The horns of the altar offered protection against human retaliation but not against divine judgment (cf. Exod 21:14: the deliberate murderer is dragged from my altar). Adonijah&#8217;s flight to the altar reflects the correct instinct that only divine protection can shelter against legitimate royal judgment — a shadow of the deeper truth that only Christ, our altar and high priest, shelters us from divine wrath.</p>",
"51": "<p>The report to Solomon: Adonijah has seized the altar&#8217;s horns and asks for Solomon&#8217;s sworn oath not to kill him. The pretender&#8217;s petition to the legitimate king is his only hope. All who have been on the wrong side of the true king must ultimately sue for mercy rather than right. The NT pattern is identical: those who opposed Christ&#8217;s appointment have no claim by right; they can only plead for mercy through the very king they wronged.</p>",
"52": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s conditional mercy: &#8220;If he shows himself a man of integrity, not a hair of his shall fall to the earth&#8221; — but if wickedness is found in him, he shall die. The condition of integrity (<em>ben ḥayil</em>) mirrors the moral demand of the covenant. The true King offers conditional pardon based on future faithfulness. Christ&#8217;s pardon is unconditional in its basis (grace alone) but calls for genuine repentance and ongoing fidelity — mercy that does not ignore moral reality.</p>",
"53": "<p>Solomon sends and brings Adonijah down from the altar; Adonijah bows before Solomon (<em>wayyishtaḥû lišlōmōh</em>). The pretender&#8217;s final prostration before the legitimate king is the resolution of the usurpation narrative — every knee bowing, even the rival&#8217;s. This anticipates the eschatological submission of Philippians 2:10–11: &#8220;at the name of Jesus every knee should bow&#8230; and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord.&#8221; Solomon&#8217;s mercy to Adonijah at this moment is typological of Christ&#8217;s patience with those who submitted to him.</p>"
},
"2": {
"1": "<p>David&#8217;s final charge to Solomon as death approaches: <em>qāraḇû yᵉmê dāwid lāmût</em> (the days of David drew near to death). David is the last of the great patriarchal figures who give a final blessing/charge before dying: Jacob (Gen 49), Moses (Deut 33), and now David. The formal testament (<em>ṣiwwāh ʾet šᵉlōmōh bᵉnô</em>) places his words within the tradition of covenant transmission at the point of death. Christ&#8217;s final discourses (John 14–17) and the Great Commission stand in this tradition.</p>",
"2": "<p>&#8220;I am about to go the way of all the earth (<em>ʾānōḵî hōlēḵ bᵉdereḵ kol hāʾāreṣ</em>). Be strong; show yourself a man.&#8221; The charge to be strong (<em>ḥăzaq</em>) and to act as a man (<em>wᵉhāyîtā lᵉʾîš</em>) echoes YHWH&#8217;s charge to Joshua at Moses&#8217; death (Josh 1:6–7). The succession of &#8220;be strong&#8221; charges — Moses to Joshua, David to Solomon — points toward the ultimate successor who needs no such charge because he is inexhaustible strength: &#8220;strong in the Lord and in the strength of his might&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 6:10'>Eph 6:10</a>).</p>",
"3": "<p>&#8220;Keep the charge of the LORD your God, walking in his ways and keeping his statutes&#8230; as it is written in the Law of Moses.&#8221; The charge to observe Torah as the condition of the Davidic covenant reaches its climax here. No Davidic king ever kept Torah fully — Solomon himself will fail catastrophically with the foreign wives (1 Kgs 11). The true Son of David who &#8220;fulfills all righteousness&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 3:15'>Matt 3:15</a>) and &#8220;did not come to abolish the Law but to fulfill it&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 5:17'>Matt 5:17</a>) is the answer to this unfulfillable charge.</p>",
"4": "<p>The Davidic covenant condition: &#8220;If your sons keep their way, to walk before me in faithfulness with all their heart and soul, a man shall never fail you on the throne of Israel.&#8221; The conditional form of the promise (<em>ʾim</em>) reveals that human fulfillment of the covenant is required but never achieved by any Davidic king until Christ. He is the one man who walks before YHWH in complete faithfulness, whose obedience &#8220;unto death, even death on a cross&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Phil 2:8'>Phil 2:8</a>) fulfills the covenant condition and secures the eternal Davidic throne.</p>",
"5": "<p>David&#8217;s charge regarding Joab: &#8220;you know what Joab son of Zeruiah did to me — what he did to the two commanders of Israel&#8230; shedding the blood of war in peacetime.&#8221; Joab&#8217;s murders of Abner and Amasa introduced blood guilt into the Davidic administration. David&#8217;s deathbed reckoning with unsettled accounts of blood guilt reflects the biblical principle that justice requires resolution — deferred but not abandoned. Christ&#8217;s atoning death is the ultimate resolution of all deferred accounts of blood guilt, paying what could not be paid in David&#8217;s lifetime.</p>",
"6": "<p>&#8220;Act according to your wisdom, but do not let his gray head go down to Sheol in peace.&#8221; David commissions Solomon to exercise royal wisdom in executing justice on Joab. The combination of wisdom and justice — act wisely but do not let the guilty go unpunished — is the profile of the ideal Davidic king. The Messiah is both &#8220;Wonderful Counselor&#8221; and the one who &#8220;shall judge the poor with righteousness&#8221; (Isa 9:6; 11:4), uniting wisdom and just judgment in one person.</p>",
"7": "<p>The counter-charge: show loyalty (<em>ḥesed</em>) to the sons of Barzillai the Gileadite who supported David in his flight from Absalom. David&#8217;s remembrance of loyalty received and loyalty owed models covenant faithfulness — <em>ḥesed</em> must be returned for <em>ḥesed</em>. The kingdom of the Messiah is characterized by <em>ḥesed</em> flowing in both directions: gratitude for faithfulness shown, and ongoing commitment to those who stood with the true king in times of crisis.</p>",
"8": "<p>The charge regarding Shimei: he cursed David viciously when David fled from Absalom, and David swore not to kill him. But now David charges Solomon not to hold him guiltless. The apparent tension — David swore not to harm Shimei himself, but charges Solomon to deal with him — reflects the principle that oaths bind the swearer, not successors. More profoundly, postponed judgment is not canceled judgment; every account not settled in one generation is passed to the next. Only Christ&#8217;s atoning work settles accounts permanently.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;You are a wise man and will know what to do with him; bring his gray head down to Sheol with blood.&#8221; David entrusts the execution of deferred justice to Solomon&#8217;s wisdom. The charge reflects that wisdom and justice are inseparable royal functions — wisdom without justice is accommodation; justice without wisdom is brutality. The Messiah&#8217;s wisdom perfectly serves his justice: he does not condemn arbitrarily but executes judgment with perfect understanding of all circumstances.</p>",
"11": "<p>David&#8217;s regnal summary: forty years total — seven in Hebron, thirty-three in Jerusalem. The mathematical precision of the regnal formula provides historical anchor and theological symmetry. David&#8217;s forty-year reign echoes Israel&#8217;s forty years in the wilderness and anticipates the Messiah&#8217;s forty days in the wilderness — the king&#8217;s formation period mirrors the covenant people&#8217;s formation period. Jerusalem receives thirty-three years of David&#8217;s reign, the number tradition assigns to Christ&#8217;s earthly life.</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;Solomon sat on the throne of his father David, and his kingdom was firmly established (<em>wattikkōn malkûtô mᵉʾōḏ</em>).&#8221; The establishment of the kingdom marks the fulfillment of the 2 Samuel 7 promise: a son of David on the throne with a firm kingdom. The phrase &#8220;firmly established&#8221; echoes YHWH&#8217;s promise to confirm (<em>kûn</em>) the Davidic dynasty. In Christ, the kingdom is finally and irreversibly established: &#8220;of his kingdom there will be no end&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 1:33'>Luke 1:33</a>).</p>",
"13": "<p>Adonijah approaches Bathsheba with a request, framing himself as peaceful (<em>šālôm</em>). The defeated pretender coming to the queen mother with a seemingly innocent request sets a political trap. Adonijah&#8217;s &#8220;peaceful&#8221; opening is immediately suspicious — those who caused upheaval rarely come with purely peaceful motives. The discernment of motives behind presented faces is a royal wisdom task that the Messiah exercises perfectly: &#8220;he did not entrust himself to them, for he knew all people&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 2:24'>John 2:24</a>).</p>",
"14": "<p>&#8220;I have a matter to discuss with you.&#8221; Adonijah&#8217;s request to Bathsheba reveals that he understands the queen mother&#8217;s intercessory role in the Davidic court. The queen mother was a formal position (<em>gᵉḇîrāh</em>) with real political influence. Adonijah&#8217;s appeal to Bathsheba is an attempt to use legitimate institutional channels for a secretly delegitimizing purpose — a warning about how religious and institutional forms can serve subversive ends.</p>",
"15": "<p>Adonijah&#8217;s claim: &#8220;the kingdom was mine and all Israel expected me to reign — yet the kingdom has turned and become my brother&#8217;s, for it was his from YHWH.&#8221; His grudging acknowledgment — <em>kî lô hāyᵉtāh malkûtô mēʿim YHWH</em> (for the kingdom was his from YHWH) — is a confession of divine appointment even while he seeks to undermine it. Acknowledging the legitimate king&#8217;s divine appointment while pursuing his throne is the characteristic posture of false claimants throughout Scripture.</p>",
"16": "<p>Adonijah frames his request as a &#8220;one small request&#8221; — the minimization of a significant demand. The rhetoric of smallness to disguise large intentions is a characteristic of manipulation. The request that follows (Abishag) is in fact a claim to royal status. The Messiah&#8217;s demands are never disguised as small: &#8220;Take up your cross&#8221; is stated plainly. The contrast between transparent costly discipleship and the pretender&#8217;s minimized demands reveals who the true king is.</p>",
"17": "<p>Adonijah requests Abishag the Shunammite as a wife — &#8220;for Solomon will not refuse you.&#8221; The request for the king&#8217;s attendant is a thinly veiled claim to royal succession; taking a predecessor&#8217;s concubine or attendant was an assertion of dynastic rights (cf. Absalom&#8217;s public appropriation of David&#8217;s concubines, 2 Sam 16:21–22). Adonijah&#8217;s request through his mother is a renewed bid for the throne dressed in domestic language.</p>",
"18": "<p>Bathsheba agrees to speak to Solomon on Adonijah&#8217;s behalf. Her willingness to advocate reflects the queen mother&#8217;s institutional role as petitioner. She is not complicit in Adonijah&#8217;s scheme — she may not have understood its political implications — but her mediation inadvertently tests Solomon&#8217;s discernment. The scene illustrates that intercessory channels can carry requests that are not what they appear; the king who receives all petitions must be able to see through them.</p>",
"19": "<p>Bathsheba goes to Solomon; the king rises to meet her and bows (<em>wayyiqqōḏ lāh</em>), then has a throne set for her at his right hand. The king&#8217;s honor to his mother — rising, bowing, placing her throne at his right — is the formal recognition of the queen mother&#8217;s status. Psalm 45:9 describes the queen at the king&#8217;s right hand; the queen mother&#8217;s throne at the Davidic king&#8217;s right hand is an institutional expression of this royal honor that finds its ultimate form in the messianic court.</p>",
"20": "<p>Bathsheba&#8217;s request formula mirrors Adonijah&#8217;s: &#8220;one small request.&#8221; Solomon&#8217;s response — &#8220;ask, my mother, for I will not refuse you&#8221; — sets up the dramatic reversal. The king&#8217;s open-ended promise to his mother creates the tension the narrative will resolve. In contrast to this human dynamic of promising before hearing, the Messiah&#8217;s promises are made with perfect foreknowledge — he never commits to what he will regret or must retract.</p>",
"21": "<p>Bathsheba&#8217;s petition: &#8220;Let Abishag the Shunammite be given to your brother Adonijah as his wife.&#8221; The request as stated sounds domestic and reasonable. Solomon&#8217;s response will expose its true meaning. The gap between the surface meaning of a request and its actual import is a recurring feature of royal narratives — wisdom consists in hearing what is actually being asked beneath what is formally said.</p>",
"22": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s penetrating response: &#8220;Why do you ask Abishag the Shunammite for Adonijah? Ask for him the kingdom also&#8230;&#8221; The king immediately sees through the diplomatic framing to the real request. The Davidic ideal of wisdom — perceiving the hidden reality behind the presented surface — is what the Messiah possesses perfectly. His wisdom cannot be manipulated by rhetorical packaging: &#8220;he knew what was in man&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 2:25'>John 2:25</a>).</p>",
"23": "<p>Solomon swears an oath: &#8220;May God punish me severely if this request of Adonijah does not cost him his life.&#8221; The oath formula (<em>kōh yaʿăśeh lî ʾelōhîm wᵉḵōh yōsîp</em>) is the strongest form of self-imprecation. Solomon&#8217;s oath to act decisively against usurpation models the Messiah&#8217;s commitment to justice — the true King does not tolerate ongoing challenges to his authority with unlimited patience, but acts with sworn commitment to protect the kingdom.</p>",
"24": "<p>&#8220;As YHWH lives — who established me and set me on the throne of David my father, and who has made me a house (<em>bayit</em>) as he promised — Adonijah shall be put to death today.&#8221; Solomon grounds his judgment in YHWH&#8217;s establishing act and the dynastic promise. The judgment on the pretender is inseparable from the affirmation of the legitimate king&#8217;s divine establishment. Justice against false claimants is the flip side of the covenant with the true king.</p>",
"25": "<p>Benaiah executes Adonijah by Solomon&#8217;s command. The appointed military officer carries out the royal decree — justice executed through proper institutional channels rather than by the king&#8217;s personal hand. The Messiah&#8217;s final judgment is also executed through appointed agents: &#8220;He has fixed a day on which he will judge the world in righteousness by a man whom he has appointed&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Acts 17:31'>Acts 17:31</a>) — judgment is certain, appointed, and properly delegated.</p>",
"26": "<p>Solomon exiles Abiathar to Anathoth: &#8220;you deserve death, but I will not put you to death at this time because you carried the ark of the Lord YHWH before my father David.&#8221; Past faithfulness earns clemency, not acquittal. Solomon&#8217;s mercy to Abiathar acknowledges the weight of covenant service while still removing him from office. The true King weighs the whole history of a life rather than only its final failure — a mercy that does not overlook sin but places it in full context.</p>",
"27": "<p>The theological comment: &#8220;So Solomon removed Abiathar from the priesthood of the LORD, fulfilling (<em>lᵉmallēʾt</em>) the word the LORD had spoken concerning the house of Eli at Shiloh.&#8221; The historian explicitly identifies this political act as prophetic fulfillment (1 Sam 2:31–35). Secular succession events are simultaneously the fulfillment of prophetic words given generations earlier. This is the hermeneutical principle of the entire OT: what seems like mere politics is the movement of redemptive history toward Christ.</p>",
"28": "<p>Joab, having sided with Adonijah, flees to the tent of the LORD and seizes the altar&#8217;s horns — the same sanctuary-refuge Adonijah had used in ch1. The repetition of the altar-flight pattern signals that this refuge cannot save those guilty of intentional bloodshed (Exod 21:14). The altar that offers refuge from human retaliation cannot shield those whose guilt the king has righteously condemned. Only Christ as both the altar and the sacrifice provides genuine refuge from divine judgment.</p>",
"29": "<p>Solomon is told Joab has fled to the altar; he sends Benaiah with the command to strike him there. The king&#8217;s willingness to carry out execution at the altar demonstrates that sanctuary law has limits — deliberate murder cannot shelter permanently behind cultic privilege. The Messiah does not allow religious formalism to become a permanent shield for moral guilt; he calls out those who make the temple &#8220;a den of robbers&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 21:13'>Matt 21:13</a>).</p>",
"30": "<p>Benaiah delivers the command; Joab refuses to leave: &#8220;No, I will die here.&#8221; The defiant soldier who spent a lifetime placing himself above law now invokes sanctuary at the end. His death at the altar is both judicial and ironic — the man of blood dies at the place of blood-sacrifice. The altar that represents atonement becomes the site of judgment for one who never sought atonement for his crimes. The spatial irony underscores the difference between using sacred space and actually submitting to the sacred reality it represents.</p>",
"31": "<p>Solomon commands: &#8220;Do as he says; strike him down and bury him. Remove from me and from my father&#8217;s house the guilt of the blood (<em>ḏamê ḥinnām</em>) which Joab shed.&#8221; The king&#8217;s motivation is not merely political purging but covenantal cleansing: removing blood guilt from the royal house. The language of &#8220;innocent blood&#8221; returned to its source echoes Deuteronomy&#8217;s purgation laws. The Messiah&#8217;s atoning death is the ultimate removal of blood guilt — not from one house but from all who take shelter in his name.</p>",
"32": "<p>YHWH will return Joab&#8217;s blood on his own head for the murders of Abner son of Ner and Amasa son of Jether — men more righteous than he. The principle of blood retribution — the wrongly shed blood returning on the wrongdoer&#8217;s head — runs through Scripture as a moral law of the covenant. Ultimately resolved in Christ: his &#8220;innocent blood&#8221; is not returned on his own head but absorbed by him, breaking the retributive cycle for all who are in him.</p>",
"33": "<p>&#8220;Their blood will come back on Joab and his descendants forever. But on David and his descendants and his house and his throne, peace (<em>šālôm</em>) from YHWH forever.&#8221; The final resolution of blood guilt — permanently settled on the guilty line, permanently removed from the Davidic line — is the peace of the messianic kingdom. The <em>šālôm</em> pronounced over David&#8217;s throne here is the seed of the eternal peace the Prince of Peace (<a class='ref' data-ref='Isa 9:6'>Isa 9:6</a>) secures for all who enter his kingdom.</p>",
"34": "<p>Benaiah executes Joab; he is buried at his home in the wilderness. The death and burial of the one whose crimes had destabilized the Davidic administration closes the account. The narrative&#8217;s insistence on burial — even for the executed — reflects the biblical respect for human remains and the hope of resurrection. Even judgment ends with burial rather than desecration, a dignity the Messiah ensures: &#8220;he had done no violence&#8230; they made his grave with the wicked&#8221; (Isa 53:9), yet he was buried in a rich man&#8217;s tomb.</p>",
"36": "<p>Solomon confines Shimei to Jerusalem: &#8220;Build yourself a house in Jerusalem and live there — do not leave to go anywhere else.&#8221; The house arrest as a condition of mercy — freedom within limits, death if the limits are violated — mirrors the Edenic pattern: blessing within the garden, death if the boundary is crossed. The grace that allows the guilty to live always comes with conditions; the Messiah&#8217;s grace is unconditional in its basis but calls for covenant fidelity in its ongoing expression.</p>",
"37": "<p>&#8220;For on the day you leave and cross the Kidron Valley, know for certain that you will die (<em>yāmôt tāmût</em>).&#8221; The Kidron Valley — the ravine between Jerusalem and the Mount of Olives — is specified as the boundary. The same valley David crossed weeping during Absalom&#8217;s rebellion (2 Sam 15:23); the same valley Jesus crosses to Gethsemane the night of his arrest (John 18:1). Geography in redemptive history is never merely physical; boundaries mark the sacred from the profane, and crossing them has covenantal consequences.</p>",
"38": "<p>Shimei&#8217;s agreement: &#8220;What you say is good; your servant will do exactly as my lord the king has said.&#8221; The initial submission and agreement is genuine — Shimei lives in Jerusalem for three years without incident. Initial submission to the king&#8217;s terms is right but insufficient; ongoing faithfulness under pressure is the test. The parable of the sower&#8217;s shallow soil receives the word with joy but falls away when difficulty comes (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 13:20-21'>Matt 13:20–21</a>) — Shimei is that soil.</p>",
"39": "<p>Three years later, two of Shimei&#8217;s servants flee to Gath to King Achish son of Maacah. Shimei is told, and he goes to retrieve them. The servants&#8217; flight provides the occasion; Shimei&#8217;s choice to go — valuing his property above his covenant with the king — reveals the shallow root of his submission. The test of covenant fidelity comes through ordinary life circumstances, not grand temptations. Shimei fails not in a moment of dramatic apostasy but in a decision that seems practically necessary.</p>",
"40": "<p>Shimei saddled his donkey and went to Gath. The deliberate detail — saddled his donkey, went, returned — emphasizes the calculation and completion of the act. Covenant violations rarely feel like violations in the moment; they feel like practical necessities. Shimei did not intend rebellion; he intended to retrieve property. The Messiah&#8217;s covenant community faces the same pressure: decisions that seem locally necessary but violate prior commitments.</p>",
"41": "<p>Solomon is informed that Shimei has left Jerusalem and returned. Royal awareness of covenant violation — even minor, even unannounced — reflects the omniscient king&#8217;s comprehensive oversight. The true Davidic King who misses nothing stands behind this detail: &#8220;nothing is hidden that will not be made known&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 10:26'>Matt 10:26</a>). The king&#8217;s knowledge of the covenant violation precedes Shimei&#8217;s summons — the king knows before the confrontation.</p>",
"42": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s question: &#8220;Did I not make you swear by the LORD and warn you — on the day you go out anywhere, know that you will die? And you said, Good; I heard it.&#8221; The king recalls both the oath and Shimei&#8217;s own agreement. The witness against Shimei is his own word. At the last judgment, the witness against the unfaithful is their own acknowledgment of the covenant they understood and accepted (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 25:26'>Matt 25:26</a>: &#8220;you knew&#8230;&#8221;).</p>",
"43": "<p>&#8220;Why then have you not kept the oath you swore before the LORD and the command I gave you?&#8221; The question exposes the gap between commitment and performance. Shimei made a public covenant oath invoking YHWH&#8217;s name and broke it for a minor convenience. The weight of oath-breaking under the Davidic covenant points to the seriousness with which the true King treats covenant fidelity — and to the redemptive work required to restore those who have broken what they swore to keep.</p>",
"44": "<p>&#8220;You know in your own heart all the evil you did to my father David.&#8221; The appeal to Shimei&#8217;s own conscience — <em>ʾattāh yāḏaʿtā ʾēt kol hārāʿāh ʾăšer yāḏaʿ lᵉḇāḇᵉḵā</em> — grounds the judgment in self-knowledge rather than external accusation. The Messiah&#8217;s judgment similarly appeals to the heart&#8217;s own knowledge: those who stand before the throne are condemned not by external information only but by their own conscience bearing witness (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 2:15-16'>Rom 2:15–16</a>).</p>",
"45": "<p>&#8220;But King Solomon shall be blessed, and David&#8217;s throne shall be established before the LORD forever (<em>lᵉʿōlām</em>).&#8221; The contrast between Shimei&#8217;s guilt and the eternal Davidic throne is the final word of the succession narratives. The throne is not threatened by Shimei&#8217;s curse or Adonijah&#8217;s coup or Joab&#8217;s murders — it stands forever because YHWH established it. The messianic throne is similarly impervious to every human opposition: &#8220;He will reign forever and ever&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 11:15'>Rev 11:15</a>).</p>",
"46": "<p>Benaiah executes Shimei; the kingdom is firmly established (<em>wattikkōn hammalkût bᵉyaḏ šᵉlōmōh</em>). The final verse of the succession narrative closes with the establishment formula that opened ch2 v12. The removal of every threat — Adonijah, Joab, Abiathar, Shimei — is not political vengeance but the purging that establishes the kingdom on a clean foundation. The messianic kingdom&#8217;s final establishment will similarly follow the removal of every rival and threat: &#8220;the last enemy to be destroyed is death&#8221; (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 15:26'>1 Cor 15:26</a>), after which the kingdom is handed to the Father, fully and eternally established.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    out_path = "data/commentary/mkt-christ/1kings.json"
    existing = load_comm(out_path)
    before = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    after = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    save_comm(out_path, existing)
    print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
    print(f"1kings mkt-christ: added up to {after - before} verses across ch1-2")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
